'''Russel E. Caflisch''' is an American mathematician.

==Biography==
Caflisch is Director of the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] at [[New York University]] (NYU), and a Professor in the Mathematics Department. He received his bachelor's degree from Michigan State University in 1975. He earned a master's degree and Ph.D. in Mathematics from the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences at New York University.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} His dissertation was titled "The Fluid Dynamic Limit and Shocks for a Model Boltzmann Equation." He has also held faculty positions at Stanford and NYU. He has served as PhD advisor for 22 students, with 55 descendants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.ams.org/id.php?id=33190|title=Russel Caflisch - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=www.genealogy.ams.org|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref> Up until August 2017, Caflisch was the director of the [[Institute for Pure and Applied Mathematics|Institute for Pure & Applied Mathematics (IPAM)]] and a professor in the Mathematics department, where he also held a joint appointment in the department of Materials Science and Engineering.<ref>{{cite web|title=IPAM Directors|url=http://www.ipam.ucla.edu/people/directors/|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>

Caflisch was a founding member of [[California NanoSystems Institute]] (CNSI).  Caflischâ€™s expertise includes topics in the field of applied mathematics, including [[partial differential equation]]s, [[fluid dynamics]], [[plasma physics]], [[materials science]], [[Quasi-Monte Carlo method|Monte Carlo methods]], and computational finance.

==Recognition==
Caflisch was awarded the [[Hertz Foundation|Hertz Foundation Graduate Fellowship]] in 1975<ref>{{cite web|title=Hertz Foundation Fellows List|url=https://hertzfoundation.org/dx/fellows/fellows.aspx|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}
</ref> and a [[Sloan Fellowship|Sloan Foundation Research Fellowship]] in 1984. He was named a fellow of the [[Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics]] in 2009,<ref>{{cite web|title=SIAM Fellows List|url=https://www.siam.org/Prizes-Recognition/Fellows-Program/All-SIAM-Fellows/Class-of-2009|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref> the [[American Mathematical Society]] in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=AMS Fellows List|url=http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list-institution|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Academy of  Arts and Sciences Fellows List|url=http://www.ucla.edu/about/awards-and-honors/faculty/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>
He was elected a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nasonline.org/news-and-multimedia/news/2019-nas-election.html|title=2019 NAS Election|publisher=National Academy of Sciences|date=April 30, 2019|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>

